## Migration Analysis

Your code has three Thread.Abort-related APIs that **throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8**:

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Control flow cleanup |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue after abort |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort equivalent needed; just continue to let
                // the while-loop condition exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive, there's nothing equivalent to Abort().
        // The thread must cooperate. Log a warning if it hasn't stopped.
        if (_workerThread?.IsAlive == true)
        {
            // Log: "Worker thread did not exit within timeout."
            // Consider: _workerThread.Join() to wait indefinitely,
            // or accept that the background thread will die at process exit.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Critical Changes to Downstream Methods

`GetNextItem()` **must** accept the token — otherwise cancellation stalls at the blocking call:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks forever, ignoring cancellation
private WorkItem GetNextItem() { ... }

// AFTER — wakes up when cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // If using a BlockingCollection<T>:
    return _queue.Take(token);

    // If using Thread.Sleep to poll:
    // Replace Thread.Sleep(ms) with token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)

    // If using synchronous I/O (socket, file):
    // Switch to async overloads or register token to close the handle
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Not passing the token to blocking calls** | `GetNextItem()` may block on a queue/socket/sleep. Without the token, `Cancel()` has no effect and the thread hangs — this is the #1 migration failure. |
| **Using `Thread.Sleep` in the loop** | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` so cancellation wakes the thread. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation — unexpected exceptions propagate. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It leaks timer/callback registrations. Implement `IDisposable` as shown. |
| **Expecting instant stop** | Cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints. If `ProcessItem` runs for minutes without checking the token, cancellation waits. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside long operations. |

## What Changed and Why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|----------------|--------|--------|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`Take`, `WaitOne`, `Delay`) — a bool cannot unblock them |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | `Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (...)` | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown in modern .NET |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | Not needed — the loop condition handles continuation |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2))` | `Join` actually waits for the thread; `Sleep` just delays the caller blindly |
